ps/2 uses a 6-pin mini-DIN connector
with a clock (CLK) generated by the device,
typically at 10-16.7 kHz
and a data line (bidirectional)

data frame structure:
each transmission consists of 11-12 bits:
1. start bit (always 0)
2. 1 byte of data (LSB first)
3. parity bit
4. stop bit (always 1)
5. optional ACK bit (host-to-device communication)

## device->host communication
1. device waits for both CLK and Data to be high (idle)
2. device pulls Data low (start bit)
3. device generates a clock pulse (~10-16.7 kHz)
4. on each falling clock edge, the host samples the Data line
5. device transmits 8 data bits, parity bit, and stop bit

## host->device communication
the host can also send commands:
1. host pulls CLK low for at least 100 micro seconds (request-to-send)
2. host pulls Data low and releases CLK
3. device generates clock pulses
4. host sends data bits on th efalling edge; device reads on rising edge
5. device sends ACK bit (pulls Data low on 11th clock)

# Scan Codes
Keyboards send scan codes representing key presses/releases. There are multipel scan code sets, with Set 2 being the most common. Each key gets a make code (pressed) and a break code (released, usually prefixed with 0xF0).
